# Pure logic vs I/O

Decisions (validation, version comparison, conflict resolution, business rules) and I/O (DB, network, file system, time lookups) belong in separate functions.

## Symptom of violation

You cannot exercise a branch in a unit test without spinning up infrastructure. If reproducing "rule X rejected the input" requires a real database or network — the decision and the I/O are fused.

## Remedy

Extract the decision into a pure function that takes plain values and returns a result. The caller owns I/O and passes results in. The orchestrator stays integration-tested; the decision becomes unit-testable.

## When not to extract

- Decision is a single expression at one call site; a test would only restate the operator.
- Function is pure orchestration with no branching beyond error propagation.
